]]\n", "text_old": "{{About|the men's team|the women's team|Belarus women's national football team}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox national football team\n| Name               = Belarus\n| Badge              = \n| FIFA Trigramme     = BLR\n| Nickname           = ''\u0411\u0435\u043b\u044b\u044f \u043a\u0440\u044b\u043b\u044b'' / ''Bie\u0142yja kry\u0142y''<br>(The White Wings)\n| Association        = [[Football Federation of Belarus]]\n| Confederation      = [[UEFA]] ([[Europe]])\n| Coach              = [[Mikhail Markhel]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://by.tribuna.com/football/1075606683.html|title=\u041c\u0430\u0440\u0445\u0435\u043b\u044c \u0432\u043e\u0437\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0432\u0438\u043b \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0443\u044e \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0438|website=Tribuna.com|date=20 June 2019|language=ru|trans-title=Markhel in now the coach of Belarus national team}}</ref>\n| Captain            = [[Alyaksandr Martynovich]]\n| Most caps          = [[Alyaksandr Kulchy]] (102)\n| Top scorer         = [[Maksim Romaschenko]] (20)\n| Home Stadium       = [[Dinamo Stadium (Minsk)|Dinamo Stadium]], [[Minsk]]\n| FIFA Rank          = {{FIFA World Rankings|BLR}}\n| FIFA max           = 36\n| FIFA max date      = February 2011\n| FIFA min           = 142\n| FIFA min date      = March 1994\n| Elo Rank           = {{World Football Elo Ratings|Belarus}}\n| Elo max            = 47\n| Elo max date       = 17 November 2010\n| Elo min            = 122\n| Elo min date       = 1997\u20131998\n| pattern_la1        = _blr18h\n| pattern_b1         = _blr18h\n| pattern_ra1        = _blr18h\n| pattern_sh1        = _blr18h\n| pattern_so1        = _blr18h\n| leftarm1           = FFFFFF\n| body1              = FFFFFF\n| rightarm1          = FFFFFF\n| shorts1            = FFFFFF\n| socks1             = FFFFFF\n| pattern_la2        = _blr18a\n| pattern_b2         = _blr18a\n| pattern_ra2        = _blr18a\n| pattern_sh2        = _blr18a\n| pattern_so2        = _blr18a\n| leftarm2           = FF0000\n| body2              = FF0000\n| rightarm2          = FF0000\n| shorts2            = FF0000\n| socks2             = FF0000\n| First game         = Unofficial:<br/>{{fb|LTU|1988}} 1\u20131 {{fb-rt|BLR|1991}} <br/>([[Vilnius]], [[Lithuania]]; 20 July 1992)<br/>Official:<br/>{{fb|BLR|1991}} 1\u20131 {{fb-rt|UKR}}<br/>([[Minsk]], [[Belarus]]; 28 October 1992)\n| Largest win        = {{fb|BLR|1995}} 5\u20130 {{fb-rt|LTU|1988}}<br/>([[Minsk]], [[Belarus]]; 7 June 1998)<br/>{{fb|BLR}} 6\u20131 {{fb-rt|TJK}}<br/>([[Barysaw|Borisov]], [[Belarus]]; 4 September 2014)<br/>{{fb|BLR}} 5\u20130 {{fb-rt|SMR}}<br/>([[Minsk]], [[Belarus]]; 8 September 2018)\n| Largest loss       = {{fb|AUT}} 5\u20130 {{fb-rt|BLR|1995}}<br/>([[Innsbruck]], [[Austria]]; 11 June 2003)\n}}\n\nThe '''Belarus national football team''' ({{lang-be|\u041d\u0430\u0446\u044b\u044f\u043d\u0430\u043b\u044c\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0437\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u0430\u044f \u0411\u0435\u043b\u0430\u0440\u0443\u0441\u0456 \u043f\u0430 \u0444\u0443\u0442\u0431\u043e\u043b\u0435}} / ''Nacyjanalnaja zbornaja Bie\u0142arusi pa futbole'') represents [[Belarus]] in international [[association football|football]] and is controlled by the [[Football Federation of Belarus]], the governing body for [[football in Belarus]]. Belarus' home ground is [[Borisov Arena]] in [[Barysaw|Borisov]]. Since independence in 1991, Belarus has not yet qualified for a [[FIFA World Cup]] or [[UEFA European Championship]].\n\n==History==\nAfter the split of the [[Soviet Union]], Belarus played their first match against [[Lithuania national football team|Lithuania]] on 20 July 1992.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://eu-football.info/_match.php?id=25095|title=Lithuania v Belarus|access-date=27 May 2019|publisher=eu.football}}</ref> Before that, several Belarusian players played for the [[Soviet Union national football team|Soviet Union national team]]. The first [[FIFA]]-recognized international was a [[Exhibition game|friendly]] against [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] on 28 October 1992, and their first win came in a match against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]] on 12 October 1994.\n\nBelarus have never qualified for either the [[FIFA World Cup]], or the [[UEFA European Championship]]. Despite the lack of any significant success during the 1990s, some notable results were still achieved, like a home win against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] in the [[UEFA Euro 1996 qualifying Group 5|qualifiers]] for [[UEFA Euro 1996|Euro 1996]], and two draws against [[Italy national football team|Italy]] during [[UEFA Euro 2000|Euro 2000]] [[UEFA Euro 2000 qualifying Group 1|qualifiers]].\n\nUnder coach [[Eduard Malofeyev]], the team came very close to playing [[Germany national football team|Germany]] in a play-off round to qualify for the [[2002 FIFA World Cup|2002 World Cup]] in [[Japan]] and [[South Korea]], but were defeated by [[Wales national football team|Wales]] in the last [[2002 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 5|group stage]] match, missing the chance to overtake [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]], who drew their last game, finishing the group second behind [[Poland national football team|Poland]].\n\nTheir [[UEFA Euro 2004|Euro 2004]] [[UEFA Euro 2004 qualifying Group 3|qualifying]] campaign was very unsuccessful as Belarus lost seven of their eight games. Around the same time, a generational change occurred and a number of players from the [[Belarus national under-21 football team|U-21 team]] (which qualified for the [[2004 UEFA European Under-21 Football Championship|2004 European U-21 Championship]]) joined the senior national team. With each subsequent head coach ([[Anatoly Baidachny]], [[Yuri Puntus]] and [[Bernd Stange]]) the team improved their attacking skills. As a result, in each subsequent qualifying tournament starting with the [[2006 FIFA World Cup|2006 World Cup]], Belarus scored more goals (total and average per game) than in previous campaigns. However, problems in defense and missed scoring opportunities prevented them from finishing higher than fourth in the group. Some notable results during this period, included a high-scoring 3\u20134 away loss to [[Italy national football team|Italy]] in the 2006 World Cup [[2006 FIFA World Cup qualification \u2013 UEFA Group 5|qualifiers]] (the first time Italy conceded 3 goals in a home qualifying game since 1983), another home victory against the [[Netherlands national football team|Netherlands]] during the [[UEFA Euro 2008|Euro 2008]] [[UEFA Euro 2008 qualifying Group G|qualifiers]] as well as an away win and a home draw against [[France national football team|France]] in the [[UEFA Euro 2012|Euro 2012]] [[UEFA Euro 2012 qualifying Group D|qualifiers]].\n\nBelarus achieved some success in minor tournaments. In 2002, the team defeated [[Russia national football team|Russia]] and [[Ukraine national football team|Ukraine]] to win the [[LG Cup (association football)|LG Cup]]. In 2004 and 2008, they won the 12th and [[2008 Malta International Football Tournament|14th]] editions of the [[Malta (Rothmans) International Tournament|Malta International Tournament]] respectively. The first with its Olympic Squad, and the later with the first team (many starters were only available for the last game against [[Malta national football team|Malta]]).\n\nDuring [[UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying]], Belarus once again finished fourth in their group. However, with Belarus managed to top their group in the [[2018\u201319 UEFA Nations League D]], Belarus qualified to the country's first ever play-offs, and is scheduled against [[Georgia national football team|Georgia]].\n\n==Home venue==\n[[File:Dinamostadiuminsk.jpg|thumb|[[Dinamo Stadium (Minsk)|Dinamo Stadium]] in Minsk is the venue for most Belarus international matches]]\nThe team played the majority of its home matches at the [[Dinamo Stadium (Minsk)|Dinamo Stadium]] in [[Minsk]].\n\nOccasionally other venues are also used: [[Molodechno]] [[City Stadium (Molodechno)|City Stadium]] in May 1996 (friendly against [[Azerbaijan national football team|Azerbaijan]]), [[Vitebsky Central Sport Complex]] in [[Vitebsk]] in November 2005 (friendly against [[Latvia national football team|Latvia]]), [[Central Stadium (Gomel)|Central Stadium]] in [[Gomel]] in October 2007 ([[Euro 2008 qualifying]] match against [[Luxembourg national football team|Luxembourg]]), [[Neman Stadium]] in [[Grodno]] June 2009 ([[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2010 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Andorra national football team|Andorra]]), [[Barysaw|Borisov]] [[Haradzki Stadium|City Stadium]] just a few days later (friendly against [[Moldova national football team|Moldova]]) and [[Regional Sport Complex Brestskiy]] in [[Brest, Belarus|Brest]] in October 2009 (another 2010 World Cup qualifier against [[Kazakhstan national football team|Kazakhstan]]).\n\nIn late 2012 Dinamo Stadium was closed for renovation and the team started alternating between different home venues: [[Central Stadium (Gomel)|Central Stadium]] in [[Gomel]] ([[2014 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2014 World Cup qualifiers]] against [[Finland national football team|Finland]] and [[France national football team|France]]), [[Barysaw|Borisov]] [[Haradzki Stadium|City Stadium]] (friendly against [[Kyrgyzstan national football team|Kyrgyzstan]]) and [[Torpedo Stadium (Zhodino)|Torpedo Stadium]] in [[Zhodino]] (friendlies against [[Montenegro national football team|Montenegro]] and [[Japan national football team|Japan]]).\n\nFrom 2014 until 2017 as well as in 2019 (UEFA Euro 2020 qualifying against Germany and Northern Ireland) Belarus played at [[Borisov Arena]]. In 2018 they returned to [[Dinamo Stadium (Minsk)|Dinamo Stadium]], which was re-opened after major renovation.\n\n==Colors==\nThroughout the 1990s and early 2000s Belarus played home games in all white, occasionally changing shorts to green. All green uniform or green jerseys/white shorts were used as away kits. Since qualifying campaign for [[UEFA Euro 2004]] Belarus changed their primary colors to red jerseys and green shorts, and away kits to all white. In 2011 home colors were changed to all red. All-White became the home colour a short time later and now appears with the pattern on the Belarus flag, with the away kit being in Black in 2016, also using an adidas template and placing the flag pattern on it.\n\n==Nickname==\nIn August 2016, the Football Federation announced that the national team's nickname would be the \"White Wings\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://abff.by/index.php?option=com_zoo&task=item&item_id=2988&category_id=2&Itemid=106&lang=ru|script-title=ru:\u0412\u043b\u0430\u0434\u0438\u043c\u0438\u0440 \u0411\u0435\u0440\u0435\u0436\u043a\u043e\u0432: \"3 \u0441\u0435\u043d\u0442\u044f\u0431\u0440\u044f \u043f\u0440\u0438\u0433\u043b\u0430\u0448\u0430\u0435\u043c \u0432\u0441\u0435\u0445 \u043d\u0430 \u043e\u0442\u043a\u0440\u044b\u0442\u0443\u044e \u0442\u0440\u0435\u043d\u0438\u0440\u043e\u0432\u043a\u0443 \u0441\u0431\u043e\u0440\u043d\u043e\u0439\"|work=abff.by|language=Russian|date=11 August 2016}}</ref> The name was influenced by the book [[The Land Beneath White Wings]] (1977) by famous Belarusian writer [[Uladzimir Karatkevich]]. The BFF's new marketing and communications director, Uladzimir Berezhkov, said: \"We are looking at various ways of establishing links with our literary heritage and cultural traditions\", commenting that \"If the Belarusian people opt to associate the team with Karatkevich, almost every phrase in the book can be used as a hashtag!\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.uefa.org/MultimediaFiles/Download/EuroExperience/uefaorg/Publications/02/39/57/73/2395773_DOWNLOAD.pdf|title=UEFA Direct&nbsp;\u2013 August/September 2016|date=3 August 2016|format=pdf}}</ref>\n\n==Kit suppliers==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Kit provider\n! Period\n|-\n|-\n| {{flagicon|GBR}} [